<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-957-574  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 957 574.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Dec 11 1989 v8 n25 p3(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Protester asks House committee to probe AF's award of SWPS. (AirForce Strategic War Planning System)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Green, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Federal Data Corp. (cases)General Dynamics Corp. (contracts).andO;Ticker:    GD.andO;Topic:     Defense ContractsLegal IssuesContractorsUnited States. House. Energy and Commerce CommitteeUnited States. Air ForceCompetitive Bidding.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Protester Asks House Committee To Probe AF's Award of SWPSandM;Federal Data Corp. of Bethesda, Md., has taken its protest of the Air ForceStrategic War Planning System (SWPS) contract award to an investigativesubcommittee of Congress.andM;Last week, company officials met with investigators from the House Energy andCommerce Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigators.andM;A subcommittee investigator said Federal Data again accused the Air Force ofaccepting a bid that later had to be revised because the contractor, GeneralDynamics Corp., switched optical-equipment subcontractors.andP;  Federal Data'sprotest of the award is pending at the General Accounting Office.andM;An investigator for the subcommittee said the meeting with Federal Data waspreliminary.andM;&quot;We haven't decided yet whether we'll conduct a full investigation,&quot; he said.andM;In July, the Air Force awarded the SWPS contract to General Dynamics, whichbid $165 million.andP;  Federal Data bid about $400 million more.andP;  At the time thecontract was awarded, Air Force officials said SWPS would provide upgradedhardware, software and communications capabilities for the Strategic AirCommand headquarters in Omaha, Neb.andM;Federal Data protested to the GAO, claiming General Dynamics switchedsubcontractors for optical-storage subsystems after the contract award.andP;  Theprotest said the new subcontractor, a Japanese company, supplied parts fromToshiba Corp.andM;This would violate restrictions on Defense Department purchase of Toshibaproducts enacted after a scandal last year, the protest said.andP;  GAO isexpected to rule on the protest next month.andM;The congressional investigator said if the subcommittee does investigate, itwill request that the Air Force Computer Acquisition Center, the procurementagent in the SWPS award, provide a copy of the service's contract withGeneral Dynamics.andM;In its protest, Federal Data requested a copy of the contract, arguing thatthe low bid could not be understood fully except by comparing each line itemof the two companies' bids.andM;AFCAC officials declined to provide Federal Data with the contract, and thesubcommittee investigator said he and his colleagues expect to encountersimilar resistance if they pursue the case.andM;Federal Data first protested the award in July, characterizing the winningbid as a buy-in by a weapons system company wanting to enter the computermarket.andP;  In September the company amended the protest to include charges thatGeneral Dynamics used bait-and-switch tactics by substituting the opticalsubsystems and using Toshiba parts.andM;In their response to the protest, Air Force officials have said they canlegally allow changes, substitutions and technical upgrades during the courseof the contract work.andP;  The protest asked GAO to cancel the award to GeneralDynamics and give the contract to Federal Data.andO;</TEXT></DOC>